\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 we have problem with the immutability. Both temporal (simultaneity) and embodied.}
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 realtionship between Creator and creature}
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.jstor.org/stable/1206056?seq=1"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24 God, Creatures, and Relations: Revisiting Classical Theism on JSTOR}}{ }
\par\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Classical theism is not prominent in many of the inquiries that belong to}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 contemporary theology and philosophy of religion. There are many rea-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 sons for this. An important reason is the close association of classical the-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 ism with the position that there are no real relations of God to creatures.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 This is only one proposition associated with classical theism, but it is one}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 of its defining and most notorious aspects. It seems to be inconsistent}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 with other biblical and theological claims about God. It seems to be bereft}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 of existential significance, and possibly even oppressive.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 But there may be reasons to revisit just this aspect of classical theism}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 and to explore its resources. I want to consider that possibility, using}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Aquinas as my resource in this article.' }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 In both the Summa Contra Gentiles and the Summa Theologiae Aquinas con-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 siders the issue of relations between creatures and God while discussing}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 the possibility of predicating relative terms of God. It is for various rea-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 sons legitimate to predicate of God terms that name relations or that en-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 tail the idea of a relation between God and creatures. Creatures, effects}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 of God, have divine power as their principle. Since "principle expresses}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 relationship to that which proceeds from it, it is evident that something}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 can be said relatively of God, with regard to His effects."2 Moreover, God,}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 as does any agent, produces something with some kind of likeness to}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Himself, and likeness is a relation of sorts.3 Indeed, it is legitimate to}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 predicate of God relative terms whose denotations require time, on ac-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 count of the temporal nature of creatures.4 The issue, then, is not whether}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 or not one can speak of God through predications that signify relations}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 with creatures. The issue is one of the significance of that activity. When}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 I speak of God in ways that signify relations with creatures, what is the}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 significance of that?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Whatever else may be this case, Aquinas argues, statements that signify}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 relations between God and creatures cannot refer to real relations to crea-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 tures that exist in God. Relations to creatures cannot exist in God as acci-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 dents in a subject, since God cannot be the subject of accidents.5 Nor can}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 relations belong to the very substance of God, since "as Aristotle says in}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 the Categories, relative terms are those 'which in their very being refer}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 somehow to something else'; so that God's substance would then have to}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 be referred to something else [oporteret quod Dei substantia, hoc ipsum quod}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 ad aliud diceretur]. But that which is essentially referred to another de-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 pends on it in a certain way, since it can neither be nor be understood}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 without it."6 It is, however, impossible that there be anything apart from}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 God without which God can neither be nor be understood.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 It is worth dwelling on this matter. Real relations between God and}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 creatures would require that the divine substance, to use language that}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Aquinas uses at this point, could neither be nor be understood apart}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 creatures. "Hence it would follow that God's substance would depend on}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 something extrinsic to it, so that He would not be, of himself, the neces-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 sary being.... Therefore such relations do not really exist in God."'}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Aquinas believes that he can show that the word "God" rightly names the}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 ultimate principle of the being of things that do exist and that can not-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 be.8 That principle must itself be "necessary," that is, something that}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 cannot not-be. Now "being," for Aquinas, signifies not only facticity but}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 also and more properly actuality, as it were the fullness of the realized}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 identity that belongs essentially to something that is."'}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The issue is not whether or not one can speak of God through predications that signify relations}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 with creatures. The issue is one of the significance of that activity. When}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 I speak of God in ways that signify relations with creatures, what is the}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 significance of that?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Whatever else may be this case, Aquinas argues, statements that }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Whatever else may be this case, Aquinas argues, statements that signify}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 relations between God and creatures cannot refer to real relations to crea-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 tures that exist in God. Relations to creatures cannot exist in God as acci-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 dents in a subject, since God cannot be the subject of accidents.5 Nor can}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 relations belong to the very substance of God, since "as Aristotle says in}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 the Categories, relative terms are those 'which in their very being refer}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 somehow to something else'; so that God's substance would then have to}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 be referred to something else [oporteret quod Dei substantia, hoc ipsum quod}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 ad aliud diceretur]. But that which is essentially referred to another de-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 pends on it in a certain way, since it can neither be nor be understood}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 without it."6 It is, however, impossible that there be anything apart from}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 God without which God can neither be nor be understood}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 t is worth dwelling on this matter. Real relations between God and}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 creatures would require that the divine substance, to use language that}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Aquinas uses at this point, could neither be nor be understood apart }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 creatures. "Hence it would follow that God's substance would depend on}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 something extrinsic to it, so that He would not be, of himself, the neces-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 sary being.... Therefore such relations do not really exist in God."'}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Aquinas believes that he can show that the word "God" rightly names the}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 ultimate principle of the being of things that do exist and that can not-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 be.8 That principle must itself be "necessary," that is, something that}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 cannot not-be. Now "being," for Aquinas, signifies not only facticity but}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 also and more properly actuality, as it were the fullness of the realized}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 identity that belongs essentially to something that is."'}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 }
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 According to Cobb, "process theology may refer to all forms of theology that emphasize event, occurrence, or\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Becoming_(philosophy)"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 b}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\cf4 ecoming}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~over\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Being"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 s}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\cf4 ubstance}{\f0\fs24\b0 . In this sense theology influenced by\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georg_Wilhelm_Friedrich_Hegel"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 G}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\cf4 . W. F. Hegel}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~is process theology just as much as that influenced by Whitehead. This use of the term calls attention to affinities between these otherwise quite different traditions."}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Process_theology#cite_note-2"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [{\f0\fs24\b0\super 2}{\f0\fs24\b0\super ]}{\f0\fs24\b0\super [}{\f0\fs24\b0\super 3}{\f0\fs24\b0\super ]}}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre_Teilhard_de_Chardin"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 P}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\cf4 ierre Teilhard de Chardin}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~can also be included among process theologians,}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Process_theology#cite_note-4"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [{\f0\fs24\b0\super 4}{\f0\fs24\b0\super ]}}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~even if they are generally understood as referring to the Whiteheadian/Hartshornean school, where there continue to be ongoing debates within the field on the nature of God, the relationship of God and the world, and immortality.}{ }
\par\plain {____}
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \uc0\u8226 	}\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Modern theologians reject the classical-theist claim that }{\f0\fs24\i1 God has no real relations to creatures}{ because they believe it makes God too metaphysically distant, undermines divine love, collapses biblical language, and is incompatible with modern philosophical commitments about personhood and relationality.}
\par\plain {But the reasons differ across theological camps. Below is the structured, multi\_angle explanation you\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re looking for.}
\par\plain 
\par\plain {Classical theism (Aquinas, Augustine, much of medieval Judaism and Islam) teaches:}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Creatures are really related to God; God is }{\f0\fs24\b1 not}{ really related to creatures.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {This protects divine }{\f0\fs24\b1 immutability}{, }{\f0\fs24\b1 simplicity}{, and }{\f0\fs24\b1 aseity}{. But modern theologians\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 especially post\_1800\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 find this metaphysics too restrictive.}
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>1. Biblical personalism<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Modern theologians argue that Scripture portrays God as:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{responding,}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{grieving,}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{rejoicing,}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{entering covenants,}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{loving,}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{forgiving.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {These are }{\f0\fs24\b1 real relations}{, not merely \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93logical relations\u8221\'94 in creatures.}
\par\plain {They claim classical theism forces us to reinterpret biblical language as metaphorical in ways that distort the text.}
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>2. Modern conceptions of personhood<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Since the 19th century, theologians have emphasized that }{\f0\fs24\b1 persons are inherently relational}{. If God is personal, then God must be relational.}
\par\plain {Thus, a non\_relational God seems:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{impersonal,}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{static,}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{incapable of mutuality.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {This is a major reason for the rise of }{\f0\fs24\b1 personalist theism}{ and }{\f0\fs24\b1 relational theism}{.}
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>3. The problem of love<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {If God has no real relations to creatures, then:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls4\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God does not }{\f0\fs24\i1 really}{ love creatures,}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God does not }{\f0\fs24\i1 really}{ respond to prayer,}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God does not }{\f0\fs24\i1 really}{ enter into covenant.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Modern theologians argue this makes divine love abstract rather than interpersonal.}
\par\plain 
\par\plain {Process theologians and open theists argue:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls5\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God is affected by creatures,}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God grows in relational knowledge,}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s experience includes creaturely actions.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {They reject classical immutability and simplicity, and therefore reject non\_relationality.}
\par\plain 
\par\plain {Modern theologians often affirm }{\f0\fs24\b1 divine passibility}{ (God can be affected). Classical theism insists on }{\f0\fs24\b1 impassibility}{ (God cannot be affected).}
\par\plain {If God can be affected, then God must have real relations.}
\par\plain {Thus, modern theologians reject the classical view.}
\par\plain 
\par\plain {Classical theism says:}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {If God had real relations, He would change. If God changed, He would not be God.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Modern theology says:}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {If God cannot have real relations, He cannot love. If God cannot love, He is not the God of Scripture.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {This is the fundamental divide.}
\par\plain 
\par\plain {____}
\par\plain {Evangelical:}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>Wayne Grudem<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls6\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God is immutable in His being.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s relationships change because creatures change.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{These relational changes do not imply change in God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s nature.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>Millard Erickson<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls7\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{Advocates \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93qualified immutability.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s character is constant, but His actions vary.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s relational changes are expressions of His eternal nature.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch 
\par\plain {If God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s knowledge of creaturely acts changes, then God\u8217\'92s mental state changes. If God\u8217\'92s emotional responses change, then God\u8217\'92s affective state changes. If God\u8217\'92s relational stance changes, then God\u8217\'92s relational properties change.}
\par\plain {Classical theists argue:}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Any change in God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s mental, emotional, or relational states is a change in God.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Thus evangelicals cannot logically maintain immutability.}
\par\plain 
\par\plain {Evangelicals affirm:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls8\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God responds}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God is affected}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God enters new relations}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God experiences sequence}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Classical theists say these are }{\f0\fs24\b1 process claims}{, not classical ones.}
\par\plain {Thus evangelicals are accused of being \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93crypto\_process theologians.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>2. Evangelical immutability is incoherent<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Evangelicals say:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls9\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God is affected}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{but God does not change}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Process theologians argue this is contradictory. To be affected }{\f0\fs24\i1 is}{ to change.}
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>3. Evangelicals treat God\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s relational acts as \u8220\'93expressions\u8221\'94 of eternal decrees<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Process theologians say this collapses relationality into determinism:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls10\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{If God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s responses are eternally fixed, they are not real responses.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{If God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s relational acts are eternally decreed, they are not relational.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Thus evangelicals affirm relationality in language but deny it in metaphysics.}
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Philosophers (e.g., Paul Helm, Brian Leftow, William Hasker) argue evangelicals create logical contradictions.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>1. God cannot be timeless and responsive<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {If God is timeless, He cannot respond. If He responds, He is not timeless.}
\par\plain {Evangelicals often affirm both.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>2. God cannot be impassible and emotionally engaged<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Evangelicals affirm \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93qualified passibility,\u8221\'94 but philosophers say:}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Either God is passible or He is not. There is no middle category.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>3. God cannot know changing facts without changing<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {If God knows \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93today is Tuesday,\u8221\'94 then tomorrow He must know \u8220\'93today is Wednesday.\u8221\'94 That is a change in God\u8217\'92s knowledge.}
\par\plain {Evangelicals say God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s knowledge changes \u8220\'93relationally,\u8221\'94 not \u8220\'93essentially,\u8221\'94 but philosophers argue this distinction is incoherent.}
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb240\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs36\b1 <$Scr_H::2>Divine impassibility is the doctrine that God does not experience pain, suffering, or involuntary emotional changes, remaining perfectly immutable and self-sufficient.<!$Scr_H::2>}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\line }
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb240\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs36\b1 <$Scr_H::2>. Paul Helm \hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2  }{\f0\fs36\b1\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93The Impossibility of Divine Mutability\u8221\'94<!$Scr_H::2>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Free full text:}{ }{\f4\fs24 https://www.theologian.org.uk/doctrine/helmdimmutability.htm}{ }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.bing.com/search?q="https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theologian.org.uk%2Fdoctrine%2Fhelmdimmutability.htm""}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24 (theologian.org.uk in Bing)}}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 Helm\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s critique:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls11\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{Any change in God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s knowledge, emotions, or relations is a }{\f0\fs24\b1 real change}{.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{Evangelical distinctions between \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93essential\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93relational\u8221\'94 change are }{\f0\fs24\b1 logically incoherent}{.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{If God responds, He changes; if He changes, He is not immutable.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {This is the most direct analytic critique of the evangelical position.}
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 he doctrine of God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s impassibility has fallen on hard times. In the era of the Suffering God and of \u8220\'93Holocaust theology\u8221\'94 scarcely anyone has a good word to say for it.}{\f0\fs24\b1\i1 [1]}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~This in itself is a striking fact, given the Christian church\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eras-long commitment to the doctrine. These days nearly everyone sees the eclipse of divine impassibility as an unqualified blessing. For them the idea is totally unscriptural, a case of \u8220\'93baptised paganism,\u8221\'94 an object lesson in what happens when theology takes its lead not from divine revelation but from Neo-Platonism.\line }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \~}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The modest aim here is to say a word or two in favour of the doctrine before it finally slips from the Christian consciousness. The words may even help, in some small way, to arrest its eclipse. I hope so. I shall try to show why impassibility is suffering, then to try to show a little of what impassibility, properly understood, means, to offer some scriptural support for it and finally to reflect a little on what divine impassibility commits us to.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \line There is, I believe, at least for Anglophones, often a basic confusion between three English words: impassivity,(the English form of impassitas), impassability, and impassibility. The Oxford Shorter Dictionary defines \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93impassive\u8221\'94 as \u8220\'93deficient or void of mental feeling or emotion; unimpressionable, apathetic.\u8221\'94 (And it also notes a \u8220\'93good sense,\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93imperturbable.\u8221\'94) It goes without saying that Christians do not wish to worship and serve an apathetic God; a God who, like a human psychotic, is unconcerned by the needs of human beings. Nor even a God who, like a Stoic philosopher, is imperturbable no matter what happens. But then to suppose that the doctrine of divine impassibility commits one to such a view is based upon simple linguistic confusion, between impassivity and impassibility\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 of which more in a moment. But first, what about impassability? If the road is blocked by ice or mud then it is impassable. There is no way through. Such an idea, applied to God, makes matters worse. For if God is not only apathetic, if he is also impassable, then there is no way open to get through to him. He must forever remain in a state of apathy; perhaps, to make matters even worse, of blissful apathy.\line }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \~There is a second reason having to do with language why impassibility is suffering an eclipse. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Impassibility\u8221\'94 is a negative term. Even when properly understood, and then applied to God, it tells us what God is not, or what God cannot do, rather that what he is like and can do. Such a negative approach to thinking about God is nowadays regarded as being too vague and insubstantial for the modern Christian church. For the modern church is impatient with learning what God is not like, she wants to know what God is like, and in particular she desperately seeks reassurance that God is like us\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 that he is accessible to our imagination, and especially in need of reassurance that he is our emotional peer. This is one reason for the current stress on biblical narrative, on the anthropomorphic and anthropopathic language of Scripture, and on Christology \u8220\'93from below,\u8221\'94 as is evidenced (in different ways) by the prevalent social trinitarianism, and by the appeal of \u8220\'93open theism.\u8221\'94 Put in conventional theological terms, in the modern Christian mind the language of divine immanence swamps the language of divine transcendence. And impassibility is part of the language\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 part of the \u8220\'93grammar\u8221\'94\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 of divine transcendence. I shall return to this point shortly and develop it.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 This contemporary craving for a human-like God is heightened by modern approaches to suffering and evil. Bonhoeffer\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s phrase, \u8220\'93Only a suffering God can help,\u8221\'94 is repeated like a mantra. There is of course a perfectly good sense to these words. God in Christ suffers in taking our sin, and so helping us in a way that nothing else can. But a suffering God who endures suffering in the same way that we suffer may help by comforting us, but he is helpless to deliver us from evil.\line }{\line }{\f0\fs24\b0 he key idea for any appreciation of the idea of divine impassibility, and of its reappropriation and defense, must be the Creator-creature distinction, and the biblical idea of divine fullness. In the case of emotions, we must focus on the idea of a divine life of unimaginable richness and constancy, not of fitfulness and spasm. In this connection it is unfair as well as unbalanced to separate the divine impassibility from all other divine characteristics and to single it out for special treatment. Divine impassibility is part of a web of ideas which constitute a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93grammar,\u8221\'94 a canonical way of talking about God, a way of articulating the reality of the divine fullness. In this respect, impassibility is an aspect of divine immutability (God cannot change or be changed), of divine simplicity (the sovereign God does not depend for this existence on \u8216\'91parts\u8217\'92 which are more fundamental than he is) of divine necessity (God exists non-dependently), and of divine eternity (God is not bound by time, with part of his life in the past, as all his creatures are). God\u8217\'92s immutability covers his will, his decrees, his promises and counsel, and of course, his emotional life. Its biblical basis is found in such passages as Jas. 1.17, Ps. 102.29, Is. 14.24, Rom. 11,.29, Heb. 6. 17: 13. 8, Is 46. 10, 2 Cor. 1 18-20.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 But none of this means that God is devoid of (what we call) feelings. He loves his creation, he cares for his people, he hates unrighteousness, and so on\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 he is pure goodness. The trouble is that we are in something of a bind when we attempt to articulate this further. When we think of constancy, steadiness, and dependability at the human level we think of people possessing dispositions that are virtuous. So a person who dashes into the icy water to save the child expresses courage, a courageous disposition. He may never have to act in this way again. But in God these dispositions are never latent, for there is no \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93slack\u8221\'94 in God, but he is utterly engaged. So what are we to make of the expressions of divine anger, or of compassion, in Scripture? We are to understand them in terms of the \u8220\'93big picture\u8221\'94 or (in more academic language) a \u8220\'93pattern of judgment\u8217\'92\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b1\i1 [2]}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~about God, and thus to see them as expressions of the divine fullness accommodated to the real-time situations of his people, their characters and needs, and of God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s purposes for them. For instance, to draw out their faith, (as with Hezekiah) or their obedience, (as with Moses) or their patience (as with Job).}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 So divine immutability does not signal total inaction or immobility, like the face of the Moon, a state incapable of personal relationship. Rather, it speaks of firmness, faithfulness, covenantal constancy, grounded in who God essentially is. Likewise divine impassibility is not impassivity, but constant goodness, variously expressed (according to God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s will and to the specifics of human history) as (for example) love, or wrath, or mercy. Such expressions are rooted in the immutability of the divine nature, the fact that God is unchangeable in goodness and perfection, and cannot be deterred or deflected by outside forces. Of course God\u8217\'92s immutable relation to his creation is not perceived as such by it, but what is perceived is a function of the situation or condition of the creaturely recipient. Just as (we say) the Sun is now setting, now rising, so God is now wise, now just, now loving etc. depending on the human circumstances in which he is \u8220\'93encountered\u8221\'94 and on God\u8217\'92s purposes in these circumstances.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 By contrast human emotion is affected by ignorance and moral weakness, by surprise, fear, partiality and physical distance. (This reminds us that a range of emotions is necessarily connected with human physical embodiment.) For instance, while all of us know that at this very moment there are hundreds of children dying in Darfur this fact fails to move us, whereas if children were dying in a similar fashion on our doorstep we would be moved to grief and compassion and action. These outbreaks of emotion would not be unrelated to our own self-interests, of course, and to what follows from the fact of our physical embodiment.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 So emotion in humans is not an unmixed good. Emotion is better than no emotion, but its expression is often the result of selfishness and ignorance. With God it is otherwise. He has an emotional life\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  he cares and loves and judges and has compassion on his sinful world. But his life\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 unlike our own emotional lives\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 is not spasmodic and moody. God does not have a temper. He cannot be cowardly or vain. Rather his \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93emotional life\u8221\'94 is an expression of his perfect goodness and knowledge. The life of God is not first passive and then reactive, as ours is, but it is wholly active.\line }{\line }{\f0\fs24\b0 or does not Scripture assert that God suffers, that he is angry, that he expresses surprise, that he fears, and laughs, and repents? Did not Christ, the Son of God, suffer? How could such a God be impassible? Then quickly\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 all too quickly\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 it is concluded that the idea of divine impassibility is the result of imposition of Scripture rather than exposition of it, of eisegesis rather than exegesis. It\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s part of an attempted theological takeover by Greek ideas. But now, it is proudly claimed, we have learned to \u8220\'93take the Bible seriously!\u8221\'94}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 Secondly, this approach to Scripture, if carried out consistently, has rather embarrassing consequences. For Scripture also says that God has eyes, ears, a backside\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 anthropomorphic language, as we quickly say. And we say that God uses such language in Scripture not because he in fact has eyes, ears and a backside but because by the use of such terms he adapts himself vividly to our way of thinking. There is something in God that corresponds to this language, which it draws attention to, even though it is not literally descriptive of God. God sees\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 what does this mean? That he has eyes? And if he eyes, does he have eyelashes and eyebrows? How many eyes does he have? Does he have 20/20 vision? None of this is appropriate. Talking in this way about God would be absurd. In saying that God sees, Scripture means (something like) God has immediate, unimpaired knowledge of what he allegedly sees. A child will readily understand this.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Why not something similar with the language about God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s emotions? Are we really to believe that God gets angry, that he is overcome with anger? That he is incapacitated by suffering? That he is paralysed with fear? Can we allow that such expressions of anger or suffering carry the connotations of surprise and ignorance and apprehension and impatience and selfish vengefulness that human emotion typically does?}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb240\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs36\b1 <$Scr_H::2>. William Hasker \hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2  }{\f0\fs36\b1\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93The Openness of God: A Reply to Critics\u8221\'94<!$Scr_H::2>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Free full text:}{ }{\f4\fs24 https://www.religion-online.org/article/the-openness-of-god-a-reply-to-critics/}{ }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.bing.com/search?q="https%3A%2F%2Fwww.religion-online.org%2Farticle%2Fthe-openness-of-god-a-reply-to-critics%2F""}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24 (religion-online.org in Bing)}}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 Hasker\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s critique:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls12\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{Evangelicals try to affirm both classical immutability and real relationality.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{This results in a }{\f0\fs24\b1 contradiction}{:}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93To be affected is to change.\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls12\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{Evangelicals end up with a God who is \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93immutable in essence but mutable in relation,\u8221\'94 which Hasker says is }{\f0\fs24\b1 metaphysically impossible}{.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Hasker is an open theist, but his critique is analytic and widely cited.}
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb240\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs36\b1 <$Scr_H::2>. Brian Leftow \hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2  }{\f0\fs36\b1\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93Eternity and Immutability\u8221\'94<!$Scr_H::2>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Free full text:}{ }{\f4\fs24 https://www.bu.edu/wcp/Papers/Meta/MetaLeft.htm}{ }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.bing.com/search?q="https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bu.edu%2Fwcp%2FPapers%2FMeta%2FMetaLeft.htm""}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24 (bu.edu in Bing)}}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 Leftow\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s critique:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls13\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{If God is timeless, He cannot respond.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{If God responds, He is not timeless.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{Evangelicals who affirm both timelessness and relational responsiveness hold an }{\f0\fs24\b1 inconsistent set of propositions}{.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Leftow is a classical theist, but his critique directly targets evangelical \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93relational immutability.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb240\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs36\b1 <$Scr_H::2>4. Nicholas Wolterstorff \hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2  }{\f0\fs36\b1\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93God Everlasting\u8221\'94<!$Scr_H::2>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Free full text:}{ }{\f4\fs24 https://www.religion-online.org/article/god-everlasting/}{ }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.bing.com/search?q="https%3A%2F%2Fwww.religion-online.org%2Farticle%2Fgod-everlasting%2F""}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24 (religion-online.org in Bing)}}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 Wolterstorff\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s critique:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls14\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{Evangelicals say God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s relational changes are \u8220\'93expressions\u8221\'94 of His eternal nature.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{Wolterstorff argues this collapses relationality into }{\f0\fs24\b1 determinism}{.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{If God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s responses are eternally fixed, they are not real responses.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {This is a foundational critique of the evangelical middle position.}
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb240\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs36\b1 <$Scr_H::2>Richard Swinburne \hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2  }{\f0\fs36\b1\i1 \loch\af3\hich\af3\dbch\af3\uc1\u8220\'93The Coherence of Theism\u8221\'94 (selected chapters)<!$Scr_H::2>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Free excerpt:}{ }{\f4\fs24 https://www.oxfordscholarship.com/mobile/view/10.1093/019823725X.001.0001/acprof-9780198237250-chapter-10}{ }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.bing.com/search?q="https%3A%2F%2Fwww.oxfordscholarship.com%2Fmobile%2Fview%2F10.1093%2F019823725X.001.0001%2Facprof-9780198237250-chapter-10""}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24 (oxfordscholarship.com in Bing)}}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 Swinburne\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s critique:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls15\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{God cannot be immutable in all respects and still have }{\f0\fs24\b1 knowledge of tensed facts}{ (\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93now,\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93today,\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93tomorrow\u8221\'94).}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{Evangelical attempts to distinguish \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93essential\u8221\'94 vs. \u8220\'93relational\u8221\'94 change fail because }{\f0\fs24\b1 knowledge is an essential property}{.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {This is one of the most influential analytic arguments.}
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.jstor.org/stable/27116825?seq=2"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24 THE OPENNESS OF GOD: HASKER ON ETERNITY AND FREE WILL HASKER ON ETERNITY AND FREE WILL on JSTOR}}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Although}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Boethius in the early 6th century thought that the concept could resolve the}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 apparent incompatibility between divine foreknowledge and human free will,}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 some contemporary philosophers, such as Alvin Plantinga, have argued that}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 eternity gives no help with this problem. Other philosophers, such as Wil-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 liam Hasker, have argued that whatever help the concept of eternity may}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 give with that puzzle is more than vitiated by the religiously pernicious}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 implications of the concept for notions of God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s providence and action in}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 time.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 In this paper, I want to examine these arguments against the doctrine of}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eternity. I will focus especially on Hasker\u8217\'92s position, but I\u8217\'92ll look}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 briefly at Plantinga\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s as well.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 In various publications, William Hasker has argued for what he calls \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93the}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 openness of God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94. It is part of the openness of God, in Hasker\u8217\'92s view, that God }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 does not have comprehensive knowledge of the future; in particular, the God of}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 open theism lacks knowledge of the future free choices of human beings.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Hasker sees his position as an alternative to classical theism, as repre-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 sented, for example, by standard Thomism, which Hasker rejects. Hasker}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 thinks that the Thomistic account of God as eternal or timeless solves the}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 problem of foreknowledge and free will only at the cost of making God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 timeless knowledge useless to God in interaction with the temporal world. 1}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Hasker says:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 I \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 regard the doctrine of timelessness as coherent and intelligible\u8230\'85. But divine}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 timelessness \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 does not help \u8230\'85 in enabling us to understand God\u8217\'92s actions in}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 providence and prophecy. (H ASKER 2004, 100)}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 In this short paper, I will first examine Hasker\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s argument for thinking}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 free will and timeless knowledge are compatible, and I will give reasons for}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 thinking that Hasker\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s argument is itself incompatible with the doctrine of}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eternity. Then I will try to show that considerations derived from the}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 doctrine of eternity yield a more effective way to argue for the same conclu-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 sion. Finally, I will use those same considerations to undercut Hasker\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 conclusion that timeless knowledge could be of no use to God in guiding his}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 actions in time.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b1\i0\cf1 Boethius, who gives the classical definition of eternity, says that eternity}
\par\plain {\f2\fs24\b1\i0\cf1 is \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93the complete possession all at once of illimitable life\u8221\'94.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Moreover, no temporal entity or}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 event can be past or future with respect to, or earlier or later than, the whole}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 life of an eternal God, because otherwise God would himself be part of}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 a temporal series.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Be-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 cause the mode of existence of an eternal God is characterized by a limitless}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 and atemporal kind of presentness, the relation between an eternal God and}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 anything in time has to be one of simultaneity.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Hasker thinks that it follows from this that we are related to God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s eternal}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 present as we are related to the future: \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93if God in his eternity looks upon our}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 time as one would look back on the past, it follows that in a certain respect we}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 can view, or rather conceive of, eternity as we conceive of the future!\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 (175).}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 And from this claim, Hasker goes on to infer that \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93eternity is like the fu-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 ture, and unlike the past, in that it is still open to our influence\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  On the doctrine of eternity, it is not}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 possible for God to be related to anything as past. On the contrary, every-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 thing in time is ET-simultaneous with the whole of God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s life. For the same}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 reason, it is not true that for an eternal God all contingency has gone out of}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 contingencies in time. God is related to contingent things as they are present,}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 but nothing about this relation renders the contingent things past or non-}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 contingent with respect to God.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Hasker:\line }
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\line }{\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u8220\'93In the philosophical lineage stretching from Parmenides to Plato to Plotinus, there is a strong metaphysical and valuational preference for permanence over change \u8230\'85. And this bias against change has been powerfully influential in classical theology, leading to the insistence on an excessively strong doctrine of divine immutability \u8230\'85. For us moderns, this preference for permanence over change is scarcely compelling. Indeed, it is arguable that in our intellectual life as well as in our general culture the pendulum has swung too far in the other direction, so that if anything at all remains constant for a while our response is one of boredom and impatience. Be that as it may, the extreme valuational preference for immutability has little hold on our thinking, and the appeal of theological doctrines based on this valuation is weakened accordingly\u8221\'94\~}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 When we turn to the task of fashioning a Christian conception of God from the resources afforded us by reason and revelation, this difference turns out to be especially crucial. For, as Hasker sees it, in carrying out this task, orthodox Christian thinkers are all engaged in so-called \loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u8216\'91perfect being theology\u8217\'92, which, he tells us, \u8220\'93is operative, both explicitly and implicitly, at many, many points in the theological tradition\u8221\'94 (p. 131). That is, we begin from the presupposition that God is an absolutely perfect being\endash a presupposition Hasker willingly embraces\endash and then we proceed to determine just which attributes are to count as divine perfections. Some attributes are relatively uncontroversial, but the traditional \u8220\'93metaphysical\u8221\'94 attributes mentioned above are not among them. As Hasker puts it, \u8220\'93I do not think it should be taken as obvious, without long and thoughtful consideration, that it is \u8216\'91better\u8217\'92 for God to be temporal or timeless, mutable or immutable, passible or impassible\u8221\'94 (p. 132). And it is precisely with regard to these abstract and esoteric attributes that the above-noted difference in metaphysical predispositions has its greatest impact.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 I will return below to the claim that classical Christian thinkers were all engaged in \loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u8216\'91perfect being theology'; let us assume for now that they were so engaged. According to Hasker, their judgments about what constitutes perfection were unduly influenced by cognitive predispositions instilled by the now defunct neo-Platonic metaphysical tradition; we, on the other hand, are in a position to correct their mistakes and thus to rescue the Biblical portrayal of God from an outmoded metaphysics that forces us to interpret an excessively large part of that portrayal as metaphorical rather than literal. In short, having been freed from classical metaphysical prejudices, we can\endash and should\endash be true to our own metaphysical predispositions:}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u8220\'93It is in the end out of the question for anyone to \u8216\'91prove\u8217\'92 that a particular conception of God is the correct one. Rather, one simply finds that a particular way of understanding the things of God makes the most sense, and provides the greatest illumination, in the overall context of one\u8217\'92s thinking and living. And so we offer a challenge to the reader, to \u8216\'91try and see\u8217\'92 whether he or she cannot find a rich and satisfying understanding of Scripture, of the Christian faith generally and of our life in Christ, seen through the lens of the openness of God\u8221\'94 (p. 154).}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Here are some examples. Nearly all analytic treatments of causality take it for granted that events, rather than stable entities, are the relata of the basic causal relation. Again, nearly all analytic treatments of action take it for granted that if the concepts action, power, and agent causality have any application at all, they are applicable only in the case of free and rational beings. Yet only a handful of pre-Humean philosophers, most notably the occasionalists, would have had even the slightest inclination to accept either of these assumptions. Again, analytic philosophers of mind almost unanimously assume that Cartesian dualism is the only remotely plausible non-materialistic solution to the mind-body problem; and given the historically conditioned patterns of thought with which we have become comfortable, even the few of us who have heard of the Aristotelian alternative are as likely as not to pronounce it unintelligible.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 The most striking example is the contemporary literature on divine simplicity. Hasker tells us that \loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u8220\'93a strong majority of Christian philosophers\u8221\'94 (p. 127) have abandoned the doctrine of divine simplicity; I submit that a \u8220\'93strong majority\u8221\'94 of contemporary Christian philosophers do not so much as understand the doctrine of divine simplicity or the metaphysical background from which it emerged. In an important recent paper Nicholas Wolterstorff traces the futility of the contemporary discussion of simplicity to a largely unnoticed difference between styles of ontology\endash more specifically, between what he calls the \u8220\'93constituent ontology\u8221\'94 characteristic of medieval metaphysicians and the \u8220\'93relation ontology\u8221\'94 that marks contemporary analytic metaphysics.\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://opentheism.info/information/openness-god-reply-william-hasker/#foot5"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [5]}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~And while Wolterstorff himself is no friend of either constituent ontology or the doctrine of God that historically developed from it, he nonetheless recognizes that a convincing case for rejecting the medieval tradition in philosophical theology can be made only from within by philosophers who understand deeply what they are rejecting.\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://opentheism.info/information/openness-god-reply-william-hasker/#foot6"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [6]}}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85}
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 The second question I wish to raise concerns the advice that we \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93try and see\u8221\'94 whether the \u8216\'91open\u8217\'92 conception of God works for us. Hasker\u8217\'92s discussion of the parable of the Prodigal Son in the present paper is meant as a test case. Ask yourself: \u8220\'93Would the parable be as gripping if we imagined the father to be immutable and impassible, or to have comprehensive knowledge of the future?\u8221\'94 I think we can agree that it would not be as gripping. But exactly why not? Well, to begin with, it is no perfection for a human father to be immovable and impassible concerning the fate of his own children\endash just the opposite, in fact. If the father in the parable were not anxious and yet hopeful, he wouldn\u8217\'92t be a very good father. Nor is it a human perfection to be omniscient, even though we can at least recognize omniscience as the limiting case of something that is a genuine human perfection. }
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Yet as Christians, illumined by divine revelation concerning the mysteries of the Trinity and the Incarnation, we have a pretty good idea of what our transcendent God would be like as a human being\endash namely, exactly like Jesus Christ, who dined with public sinners, thus exciting the murmurs that prompted the parable of the Prodigal Son. According to the traditional Christian understanding of God, it is precisely in the person of our Lord Jesus Christ that the impassible, immutable, eternal God becomes passible, mutable, and time-bound. We Christians don\loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u8217\'92t need to invent an \u8216\'91open\u8217\'92 conception of the divine nature in order to marvel at the \u8220\'93folly\u8221\'94 of a risk-taking, passible God; all we need to do is to contemplate Christ crucified.\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://opentheism.info/information/openness-god-reply-william-hasker/#foot7"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [7]}}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Let me expound on this just a bit. St. Thomas claims, pace St. Anselm, that in natural theology we do not begin with a direct positive (or \loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u8216\'91quidditative\u8217\'92) concept of God\endash that is, a concept which would allow us to situate the divine nature within a taxonomy of genera and species and thus to initiate a systematic inquiry into its positive properties. Instead, we are forced to reason discursively from certain evident features of the sensible world to the existence of a First Efficient Cause of those features, and then to argue from the descriptive concept First Efficient Cause to the conclusion that the being whose existence has been proved must be radically different intriniscally from the ordinary sensible entities that we do have direct positive concepts of. The upshot of this via remotionis is that the First Cause is \u8220\'93perfect in every way\u8221\'94.\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://opentheism.info/information/openness-god-reply-william-hasker/#foot10"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [10]}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~It is only afterwards\endash in Phase 3\endash that we try to isolate a set of pure perfections which, if abstracted from the restrictive conditions under which they occur in creatures, can be attributed literally, albeit analogically, to the Creator.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 In effect, then, the via remotionis constitutes an inquiry into the difference between Creator and creature. And within St. Thomas\loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u8217\'92s system a being capable of creating ex nihilo is ultimately characterized in two basic and, as I have argued elsewhere,\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://opentheism.info/information/openness-god-reply-william-hasker/#foot11"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super [11]}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~complementary ways, one stemming from the Aristotelian tradition (Pure Actuality) and the other stemming from the Platonic tradition (Unparticipated Being). Within their respective traditions, these are limiting notions which strain our cognitive and imaginative resources but which for that very reason provide us with a powerful characterization of the ontological abyss that divides the transcendent Creator of all things from the entities he creates. In the Thomistic system, then, there is no doubt about the utter \loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u8220\'93otherness,\u8221\'94 incomprehensibility, and ineffability of the divine nature.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Why is this a serious omission? As indicated above, a metaphysical conception of the divine nature helps us divide the Scriptural descriptions of God into the literal and the metaphorical. The authors of The Openness of God object to the division made on the basis of the traditional conception of God; in particular, they claim that many Scriptural descriptions of God are unjustifiably classified as metaphorical by appeal to the negative properties (immutability, eternality, impassibility, simplicity) constitutive of the classical notion of divine transcendence. However, it is not at all clear on what basis the authors are making their own division into the literal and the metaphorical. Why, for instance, do they cling to the idea that God is immaterial and thereby relegate a whole host of Scriptural descriptions of God to the realm of the metaphorical, given that immateriality is just another one of those \loch\af5\hich\af5\dbch\af5\uc1\u8216\'91Hellenistic\u8217\'92 divine attributes that has little appeal for the modern mind? The authors insist, after all, that God has genuine emotions, and many of us who reject Cartesian dualism think that in the case of human beings certain bodily changes are essential to the having of emotions properly so-called. What makes the authors think that this is not true in the case of God as well? One might even perversely suggest that the \u8220\'93whole emotional content\u8221\'94 of the parable of the Prodigal Son is \u8220\'93profoundly altered\u8221\'94 if we imagine that the father, because he has no body, is unable literally to embrace his son or to share the fatted calf with him.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 }
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 At the heart of this shift is the view of \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8220\'93open\u8221\'94 or \u8220\'93freewill theism,\u8221\'94 promoted by a growing number of evangelicals such as Clark Pinnock, John Sanders, Richard Rice, William Hasker, David Basinger, Robert Brow, and Gregory Boyd, which proposes to be a \u8220\'93new\u8221\'94 understanding of God for our generation, a middle position between classical theism and process thought.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://learntheology.com/the-openness-of-god-a-critical-assessment.html#_ftn3_9438"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super 3}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~As the proponents of this view tell us, no longer should we view God as the sovereign Lord who for his own glory works out all things according to the counsel of his will. Rather, we should view God as the self-limiting, fellow sufferer, and loving parent who relates to his creatures in such a way that he comes to know events as they take place since he does not know the future in exhaustive detail before it happens.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Without doubt, this recent debate within evangelical theology is a symptom of an incredible division within evangelicalism-at-large. It is important to stress that this debate between open and especially classical theism is not merely the age-old debate between Calvinism and Arminianism over perennial issues of divine sovereignty, fore-knowledge, and providence, as some would have us believe.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://learntheology.com/the-openness-of-god-a-critical-assessment.html#_ftn4_9438"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super 4}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~Rather it is a debate that goes to the very heart and soul of historic Christian theology. Theology, as J. I. Packer reminds us, is a \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8220\'93seamless robe, a circle within which everything links up with everything else through its common grounding in God.\u8221\'94}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://learntheology.com/the-openness-of-god-a-critical-assessment.html#_ftn5_9438"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super 5}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~In other words, theological doctrines are much more organically related and intertwined than sometimes people realize. That is why reformulation in one area of doctrine, especially in our view of theology proper, will inevitably affect our\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 whole}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~theology. Clark Pinnock and open theism advocates realize the importance of this very point. Pinnock rightly points out that \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8220\'93no doctrine is more central than the nature of God. It deeply affects our understanding of the incarnation, grace, creation, election, sovereignty, and salvation.\u8221\'94}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://learntheology.com/the-openness-of-god-a-critical-assessment.html#_ftn6_9438"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super 6}}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~That is why, in my view, this recent shift within evangelicalism literally to redefine God is no minor debate. In the end, if this viewpoint is adopted, it will redefine the very structure of Christian theology in disastrous ways\hich\f6 \emdash \loch\f6 ways that we are just beginning to see.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://learntheology.com/the-openness-of-god-a-critical-assessment.html#_ftn7_9438"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super 7}}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 From a Christian perspective, love is the first and last word in the biblical portrait of God. According to\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/1%20John%204.8;esv?t=biblia"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 1 John 4:8}}{\f0\fs24\b0 : \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8220\'93Whoever does not love does not know God, for God is love.\u8221\'94 The statement\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 God is love is as}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~close as the Bible comes to giving us a definition of the divine reality\loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8230\'85. Love is not something God happens to do, it is the one divine activity that most fully and vividly discloses God\u8217\'92s inner reality. Love, therefore, is the very essence of the divine nature. Love is what it means to be God.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://learntheology.com/the-openness-of-god-a-critical-assessment.html#_ftn11_9438"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super 1}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 1}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 It cannot be emphasized enough that open theism\loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8217\'92s embrace of libertarian freewill is not a minor point but rather it is central to its very proposal. In fact, open theists, in my view, are quite consistent (i.e., logically, not biblically) in noting two major entailments that result from their acceptance of libertarian free will: a reduced view of divine sove\line reignty and a redefined view of divine omniscience.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Because God has chosen to create free human creatures, he has voluntarily chosen to limit himself in order to invite human beings to have dominion over the world as fellow-partners with him. However, since God has delegated power to his creatures, he has chosen to make himself vulnerable\hich\f6 \emdash \loch\f6 i.e., a risk-taker. The entailment of this for divine sovereignty is that God\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 cannot}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~guarantee that nothing can go contrary to his will, but rather that \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8220\'93God is able to deal with any circumstances that may arise\u8221\'94}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://learntheology.com/the-openness-of-god-a-critical-assessment.html#_ftn16_9438"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super 1}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 6}{\f0\fs24\b0 \hich\f6 \emdash \loch\f6 not unless he intervenes, in such a way as to take away our freedom. Open theists believe that God has the capacity to intervene in this way to \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8220\'93keep things on track.\u8221\'94 However, they deny that God could consistently and pervasively exercise his power to intervene in this manner given his commitment to create and uphold libertarian freewill.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://learntheology.com/the-openness-of-god-a-critical-assessment.html#_ftn17_9438"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super 1}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 7}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~So, in the end, God must respond and adapt to surprises and to the unexpected. Clark Pinnock states it this way: \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8220\'93God sets goals for creation and redemption and realizes them ad hoc in history. If Plan A fails, God is ready with Plan B.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 In addition, given libertarian freewill, open theists maintain that God is omniscient (i.e., knowing all that can be known), but his knowledge does not include the future free actions of human beings since it is not logically possible to know those actions before they are chosen.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://learntheology.com/the-openness-of-god-a-critical-assessment.html#_ftn19_9438"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super 1}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 9}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~For open theists, God\loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8217\'92s knowledge includes all things past and present as well as the range of future possibilities, but even God cannot know what will actually happen in the future until it happens.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://learntheology.com/the-openness-of-god-a-critical-assessment.html#_ftn20_9438"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super 2}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 0}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~Hence, to a large extent, reality is \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8220\'93open\u8221\'94 rather than closed. As Pinnock reminds us,}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Genuine novelty can appear in history which cannot be predicted even by God. If the creature has been given the ability to decide how some things will turn out, then it cannot be known infallibly ahead of time how they will turn out\loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8230\'85. I stand against a classical theism which has tried to argue that God can control and foresee all things in a world where humans are free.}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://learntheology.com/the-openness-of-god-a-critical-assessment.html#_ftn21_9438"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super 2}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 1}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 Even in this brief description of open theism, it should be quite obvious that open theism is a major departure from historic Christianity\loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8217\'92s understanding of God. With its denial of God\u8217\'92s ability to know future free human choices; its presentation of an ad hoc deity viewed either as the \u8220\'93master chess player\u8221\'94 or \u8220\'93ultimate psychoanalyst\u8221\'94 working out his intentions for the world in response to our actions;}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://learntheology.com/the-openness-of-god-a-critical-assessment.html#_ftn22_9438"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\super 2}}{\f0\fs24\b0\ul\ulc0\super\cf4 2}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~its over-emphasis on divine love at the expense of God\loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8217\'92s holiness, majesty, and glory; open theism, if adopted, presents a serious challenge to Christian theology. But what are the arguments given for such a radical view? And especially what are the Scriptural arguments? Let us now briefly turn to four main arguments for the view under the following categories: biblical, philosophical, historical, and practical.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 What are we to think of open theism? There is certainly more that can be stated than I have said in this article, but my conclusion regarding the open theist proposal is that it must be rejected. Yes, it is always necessary to go back and rethink cherished viewpoints, especially when it comes to our doctrine of God. We are all guilty of attempting to shrink God and bring him down to our level, and that is why we constantly need to go back to Scripture time and time again. However, I am convinced that the open theist proposal is not the direction to go. At too many points it is exegetically unconvincing, historically reductionistic, and theologically dangerous.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Why do I think that the proposal of open theism has a problem upholding this view of Scripture? Because given its acceptance of libertarian freewill and its understanding of divine sovereignty, how can God infallibly\~}{\f0\fs24\b0\i1 guarantee}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~that what the human authors of Scripture freely wrote was precisely what he wanted written? The only way around this is either to affirm that God dictated the text or that the biblical authors \loch\af6\hich\af6\dbch\af6\uc1\u8220\'93just happened\u8221\'94 to write everything that God wanted them to write, without error. But both of these options are very difficult to maintain}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 I}{\f0\fs24\b0  think he likely recognizes that it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s blatant circular reasoning and purely designed to try and get people onto a dialogue tree so you can get them to a point where you can say \u8220\'93hahah you have no foundation for reason!\u8221\'94 and pretend you\u8217\'92re not relying on the exact same logical axioms as everyone else.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 It\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s not a serious philosophical position, it\u8217\'92s laughable nonsense to anyone that has seriously spent five minutes thinking about it who isn\u8217\'92t a moron, whether they\u8217\'92re a theist or an atheist.}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 and then when you show that using a banana as your foundation of logic has just as much justification as their using the god of the bible, they reply with 'but you don't really believe that, I actually believe it,' as though that is an indictment of you rather than embarrassing for them.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\plain {Can we stop taking peterson seriously?}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 Well, it depends on what you mean by a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93serious person,\u8221\'94 doesn\u8217\'92t it? Are we talking about someone who earnestly contends with the unbearable weight of existence, who stares into the abyss of chaos and voluntarily chooses to act with integrity? Or do you mean someone who performs a narrow academic mimicry of seriousness polished, sterile, ideologically obedient the kind of person who wins applause from institutions that mistake jargon for wisdom? Because if that\u8217\'92s your standard, then seriousness has become a costume, not a calling. True seriousness is not about presentation. It is about responsibility. And responsibility, properly understood, is mythic in scale. It\u8217\'92s the journey of the hero in Jungian terms, the one who confronts the unknown, the dragon of chaos, and returns transformed. That figure doesn\u8217\'92t follow the script. He breaks it and rebuilds it with truth.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 And let\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s not kid ourselves in today\u8217\'92s cultural climate, the phrase \u8220\'93not a serious person\u8221\'94 is almost always wielded as a tool of moral policing by the authoritarian left, by ideologues who have appointed themselves arbiters of what counts as \u8220\'93acceptable\u8221\'94 discourse. These are the same people who preach tolerance while enforcing conformity, who demand nuance while refusing ambiguity. They don't want seriousness. They want obedience dressed up as intellectual rigor. They want ritual purity, not moral courage. And anyone who steps outside their prefabricated ethical architecture, anyone who dares to laugh at the wrong time, to question the wrong dogma, to say something that reveals a deeper, archetypal truth that person must be cast out, labeled unserious, dangerous, absurd.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 But the prophets in the Old Testament weren\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t \u8220\'93serious\u8221\'94 by the standards of their day either. Neither was Socrates. Neither was Christ, who flipped tables and spoke in parables so cryptic they still confound us. The real pattern here is ancient. The hero, the truth-teller, the one willing to confront chaos and speak, is almost always misunderstood by the crowd. Because the crowd wants comfort, not truth. So before you declare someone unserious, ask yourself what dragon they\u8217\'92re facing that you\u8217\'92re too afraid to look at. Because it might be that their very refusal to meet your standard is the most serious act of all.}
